BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"Northwestern": "https://www.blockmuseum.northwestern.edu/cinema/2026/ouilmette-2025-with-sharon-hoogstraten.html"}
X-SOURCE-ID:northwestern
SUMMARY:Film Screening: OUILMETTE (2025) with Sharon Hoogstraten & Susan R
 oe Musacchio (Kelsey)
DTSTART;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260314T180000Z
DTEND;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260314T190000Z
UID:eb0e061ca1b02fa631729144267df5a0@northwestern.edu
DESCRIPTION:In recognition of Women’s History Month\, the Gichigamiin In
 digenous Nations Museum\, Evanston History Center\, Wilmette History Museu
 m\, and Northwestern University’s Block Cinema present a special screeni
 ng of the recent documentary film Ouilmette.\n \nAbout the film:\nOUILMET
 TE (Susan Roe Musacchio Kelsey\, 2025\, 30 min\, Digital)\nSharon Hoogstra
 ten (Citizen Potawatomi) searches for her Indigenous Chicago heritage\, tr
 acing the stories of her ancestors connected to Archange Ouilmette and the
  region’s early Native communities. Following a path from Chicago to Iow
 a and eventually Kansas\, the film explores the forced removals that resha
 ped Native families and histories. Along Lake Michigan and through histori
 cal records\, Sharon pieces together a story long absent from public memor
 y. This film was created to present Chicago’s Native history\, honoring 
 the resilience of those who were displaced and illuminating the enduring c
 onnection between people\, place\, and memory. Produced by Susan L. Kelsey
  in partnership with Sharon Hoogstraten. Native American music by Mark Jou
 rdan (Ho-Chunk)\, Elexa Dawson (Citizen Potawatomi)\, and William Allison 
 Buchholtz (Algonquin).\n \nThe screening will be followed by a Q&A with S
 haron Hoogstraten and filmmaker Susan L. Kelsey.\n \n \nFREE & OPEN TO A
 LL
LOCATION:Block Museum of Art\, Mary and Leigh\, 40 Arts Circle Drive\, Eva
 nston\, IL
URL:https://www.blockmuseum.northwestern.edu/cinema/2026/ouilmette-2025-wi
 th-sharon-hoogstraten.html
X-SOURCE:Northwestern University
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"North Shore Center": "https://northshorecenter.org/event/nasinnia/"}
X-SOURCE-ID:north_shore_center
X-SOURCE:North Shore Center
DTSTART;TZID=America/Chicago:20260314T190000
DTEND;TZID=America/Chicago:20260314T190000
DTSTAMP:20260314T215433
CREATED:20260226T171646Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260303T182038Z
UID:10001365-1773514800-1773514800@northshorecenter.org
SUMMARY:NASINNIA
DESCRIPTION:The Hromovytsia Ukrainian Dance Ensemble welcomes the spring season with our newest production\, NASINNIA. Inspired by the imagery of wheat – a foundational symbol of life\, endurance\, and beauty of the Ukrainian spirit – this production honors the rich history of Ukraine\, the resilience of our ancestors\, and the eternal cycle of growth and strength held within every seed we plant across generations. Join us for this new chapter as we celebrate storytelling through dance and honor the birth of new beginnings.
URL:https://northshorecenter.org/event/nasinnia/
LOCATION:George Van Dusen Theatre
CATEGORIES:Dance
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"Northwestern": "https://wirtz.northwestern.edu/danceworks-2026/"}
X-SOURCE-ID:northwestern
SUMMARY:Danceworks 2026: Semiquincentennial
DTSTART;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260314T190000Z
DTEND;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260314T201500Z
UID:90f04e4cbc9d23a89c90bcd3b03fe028@northwestern.edu
DESCRIPTION:Artistic Director Melissa Blanco Borelli\nAs we mark the 250th
  birthday of the United States\, what do we have to celebrate? The ghosts 
 of our nation's past—slavery\, genocide\, extraction—are active forces
  haunting our burning present.\nDanceworks 2026 gathers choreographers\, d
 ancers\, and audiences to ask: What does it mean to move together in a tim
 e of unraveling? How do we move through a world where some bodies are deem
 ed disposable\, where borders harden as seas rise\, where the very ground 
 beneath us is contested?\nIn this space\, we don’t promise harmony. We o
 ffer the friction of real encounter. Through choreography and improvisatio
 n\, we explore the politics of presence: the radical act of showing up\, i
 n all our differences\, when everything tells us to retreat. Can collectiv
 e movement—breathing\, sweating\, grieving in rhythm—forge something b
 eyond mere survival?
LOCATION:Wirtz Center: Josephine Louis Theater\, 20 Arts Circle Drive\, Ev
 anston\, IL
URL:https://wirtz.northwestern.edu/danceworks-2026/
X-SOURCE:Northwestern University
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"Evanston Made": "https://evanstonmade.org/event/the-factory-theater-presents-kubrickian/2026-03-14/"}
X-SOURCE-ID:evanston_made
X-SOURCE:Evanston Made
DTSTART;TZID=America/Chicago:20260314T200000
DTEND;TZID=America/Chicago:20260314T220000
DTSTAMP:20260314T215611
CREATED:20260113T220330Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260113T220330Z
UID:10024043-1773518400-1773525600@evanstonmade.org
SUMMARY:The Factory Theater Presents “Kubrickian\,” Feb. 13 - Mar. 15
DESCRIPTION:The Factory Theater\, 1623 W. Howard St.\, is proud to present Kubrickian\, February 20 – March 15\, written by Zack Peercy and directed by AJ Schwartz.  \nTrapped in a white space\, three men who should be focused on escape or explanation can’t seem to stop talking about acclaimed film director Stanley Kubrick. This trippy existential show is a haunting and hilarious look at masculinity\, creativity\, and capitalism. \nThe regular performance schedule is Fridays and Saturdays at 8 p.m. Sundays at 3 p.m. The Tickets are $30 and may be purchased through the box office by calling 312-275-5757 or by visiting TheFactoryTheater.com.
URL:https://evanstonmade.org/event/the-factory-theater-presents-kubrickian/2026-03-14/
