BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"Cityspark Evanston": "https://www.climateactionevanston.org/nurturingnature/healthy-people-healthy-planet-experimental-evidence-for-policy-and-behavior-transformation"}
X-SOURCE-ID:cityspark_evanston
SUMMARY:Healthy People\, Healthy Planet: Experimental Evidence for Transfo
 rmation
DTSTART;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260318T183000
DTEND;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260318T193000
UID:260107Sr5bUwYuYky4ZVa_NsyARQ
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://citysparkstorage.blob.core.windows.net/p
 ortalimages/portalimages/OrVT7epDJ0CRqkLdgNSpnw.large.jpg
DESCRIPTION:How does Nature impact Human Health? Why is this important to 
 maintaining a healthy planet? Humans\, nature\, and the planet exist in a 
 dependent and reciprocal relationship. In this presentation\, we will expl
 ore the role that basic research on the health benefits of nature to human
 s can play in evoking individual behavior and social-political change need
 ed to enhance humans’ commitment to maintaining the health of our planet
 .\n\nDr. Horton received her Bachelor’s of Science in Zoology from the U
 niversity of Washington and her PhD in Biology from the University of Utah
 . She is currently an Associate Professor of Research in the Department of
  Anthropology\, subfield Biological Anthropology\, at Northwestern Univers
 ity. As a human biologist\, she combines the principles of biological ant
 hropology\, ecology\, evolution\, and physiology to investigate the mechan
 isms by which environmental conditions alter physiology and mental health.
   More generally\, she applies her work to help generate public understan
 ding of the reciprocal relationship between human and planetary health wit
 h the goal of affecting public policy and programs.
URL:https://www.climateactionevanston.org/nurturingnature/healthy-people-h
 ealthy-planet-experimental-evidence-for-policy-and-behavior-transformation
X-SOURCE:CitySpark Evanston
END:VEVENT
